<div class="header"><h1>Should Low Sodium Diet Avoid MSG?</h1></div>
<div class="body">

<p>If you are following a low sodium diet, it is generally recommended to
avoid or limit the use of flavor enhancers, such as MSG (monosodium
glutamate), as they can contribute to your overall sodium intake. While MSG
is not a source of sodium on the label itself, it is often used in conjunction
with salt and other sodium-containing ingredients, which can add to the sodium
content of the foods in which it is used <sup><a href="#src-na-1">1</a>.</sup></p>

<p>It is important to note that flavor enhancers, including MSG, are not
essential for human health and are used mainly to improve the taste and appeal of
foods. If you are following a low sodium diet, it is generally recommended to
focus on whole, unprocessed foods that are naturally low in sodium, such as
fresh fruits and vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains. These foods can help
you meet your nutrient needs while keeping your sodium intake within the recommended
range.</p>

<p>If you are concerned about the sodium content of the foods you eat, it is recommended
to read food labels carefully and to choose foods that are low in sodium. You
can also try using herbs, spices, and other flavorful ingredients to add flavor
to your foods without the need for added sodium or other flavor enhancers.</p>

